question_body: My doctor told me that I should get a mammogram every year. What exactly is a mammogram?
answer1_body: A mammogram is an X-ray picture of the breast. Doctors use a mammogram to look for early signs of breast cancer. Regular mammograms are important because they can detect breast cancer early, when it is most treatable.
answer2_body: A mammogram is a low-dose X-ray examination of the breast tissue. It is used to detect and diagnose breast cancer in women. During a mammogram, your breasts are compressed between two plates for a few seconds while an X-ray image is taken. The compression helps flatten the breast tissue so that it can be viewed more clearly on the X-ray image. Mammograms are usually performed annually starting at age 40 or earlier if you have a family history of breast cancer. They are also recommended for women who have had radiation therapy to the chest area.

question_body: What is the difference between a sprained ankle and a broken ankle?
answer1_body: A sprained ankle is an injury to the ligaments of the ankle, while a broken ankle is a fracture in one or more of the bones that make up the ankle joint. Both can be painful and require medical attention, but a broken ankle is typically more serious and may require immobilization or surgery.
answer2_body: A sprained ankle occurs when one or more ligaments in the ankle are stretched or torn, causing pain, swelling, and limited mobility. On the other hand, a broken ankle (also known as an ankle fracture) occurs when one of the bones in the ankle joint breaks or cracks. This can be caused by a sudden twisting motion, falling from a height, or direct trauma to the ankle. While both conditions can cause pain and discomfort, a broken ankle typically requires medical attention and may require surgery to repair the damaged bone. In contrast, a sprained ankle can often be treated with rest, ice, compression, and elevation (RICE), although in severe cases, it may also require medical attention.

Both can be painful and require medical attention, but a broken ankle is typically more serious and may require immobilization or surgery.
